Manhattan Deli has a lot of really good food, the building is older and really fun to look at, and the speed of service is also really good. The only reason it's not 5 stars is that, until recently, I've never really felt welcome there. I always kinda felt like I was burdening them whenever I ordered but the food outweighed that feeling. But recently there is a new girl taking orders and has made me actually feel welcomed. If that continues this will be a 5 star place in my book!

Was excited to try the place, but disappointed with the results. I went into it expecting something similar to gandolfos, with a huge menu and classics from Manhattan, particularly a great pastrami sandwich. It felt more like a mom and pop sandwich shop with soup.  Sandwich was alright, but nothing special, menu size doesn't even begin to compare with gandolfos. I didn't try any soup, but regretted not giving it a chance, since I will probably not return.

Manhattan Deli offers great soups and sandwiches in the downtown area. This is a very overlooked place to eat. I've never once been disappointed, nor have I ever noticed a large crowd that you might find at other eateries in downtown. There is plenty of seating and it is easy to get to. Definitely worth checking out for a quick, cheap bite to eat for lunch.

2 stars means I hate spending money when I could have done better.  It's not often I choose to go downtown to eat.  I felt like a deli and I wanted atmosphere.  Boy did the stars on this page lie.  The bread...soft.  Good compliment done.  The rest of the sandwich was bland, boring and regrettably paid for.  It's walk up to the cashier and order...help yourself to chips and drink so yeah, I could have got this and flavor from other delis.  Paper plates always make me feel unwelcome.  Even those little plastic baskets with paper thrown in is better than styro.  The atmosphere is compact and compartmentalized.  Though I liked the ability to hear myself think let alone conversations with friends it was overwhelmed by the feeling of eating in someones bank office circa 1940s.  Long winded...oh well.  I'm still looking for that Golden Panini and the chains aren't doing it for me. I miss NYC and I'll pay double for a sandwich like that.  Did I mention it came with pickle....
